/*
Problem: Squares of a Sorted Array

Pattern: Two Pointers / Merge Sorted Arrays

Difficulty: Easy

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(n)

The main problem occured (mainly because of the negative elements) :

* The original array is sorted.
* Negative numbers become positive after squaring.
* The squared negative part will be in decreasing order.
* The squared positive part will remain in increasing order.

My Approach:

1. Split the array into:

   * Negative numbers
   * Non-negative numbers

2. Square all elements.

3. Reverse the squared negative array so that it becomes sorted.

4. Merge the two sorted arrays using two pointers.

Example:

nums = [-4, -1, 0, 3, 10]

Negative part:
[-4, -1] -> [16, 1] -> reverse -> [1, 16]

Positive part:
[0, 3, 10] -> [0, 9, 100]

Merge:
[0, 1, 9, 16, 100]

Learnings:

* A sorted array may become unsorted after applying a transformation.
* Splitting the array into sorted regions can simplify the problem.
* The merge technique from Merge Sort can be used to combine two sorted arrays efficiently.
* Always think about the properties of the input before jumping into coding.
  */
